{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519409"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13011"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13011"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.08,0.61,0.17,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109029"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5448"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13011"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"671"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40686"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109029"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old non-Indigenous man presents to an urban General Practice clinic with a five-day history of itchy, painful blisters on his left leg. The lesions began as red, raised areas that developed into fluid-filled blisters which subsequently ruptured. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are two small vesicular lesions with honey-coloured crusting on his left leg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral erythromycin","Intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin","Topical mupirocin","Oral acyclovir","Topical clotrimazole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of non-bullous impetigo, a superficial bacterial skin infection typically caused by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E. The progression from red, raised areas to vesicles that rupture and form honey-coloured crusts is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical mupirocin\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for localised impetigo (\u22643 sores) in immunocompetent patients. It provides targeted antimicrobial therapy with minimal systemic absorption and excellent efficacy against the causative organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral erythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for localised disease in an otherwise healthy patient. Systemic antibiotics are reserved for extensive disease, systemic symptoms, or treatment failure with topical therapy. Additionally, there are concerns about increasing bacterial resistance to macrolides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is an option for treatment of impetigo where there is a high risk of acute rheumatic fever. It can be a useful option for impetigo treatment where adherence to antibiotics is difficult, as it only requires a single dose. This patient does not fit into a high-risk category.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication used for herpes simplex or varicella zoster infections. While these can present with vesicles, they typically cause grouped vesicles with an erythematous base and do not form honey-coloured crusts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical clotrimazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal agent used for conditions like tinea or candidiasis. Fungal infections typically present with scaling and erythema rather than vesicles and crusting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topical mupirocin is first-line treatment for localised impetigo in immunocompetent patients","Non-bullous impetigo typically presents with honey-coloured crusts following rupture of vesicles"],"references":["Nardi NM, Schaefer TJ. Impetigo. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2022 Oct 19]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430974/","Impetigo. In: BMJ Best Practice [Online]. [Cited 2023 Jun 7]. Available at: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/476","Cole C, Gazewood J. Diagnosis and treatment of impetigo. Am Fam Physician. 2007 Mar 15;75(6):859-64. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17390597/","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13011"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T09:17:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T09:18:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5448"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109029"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":n